# CEM — Requirements Stage Specification

This document defines the Requirements stage as a general, reusable part of the Cyples Engineering
Methodology (CEM) pipeline. It is domain-independent — the same rules apply whether the system being
described is mechanical, electrical, software, or any mix. A worked example applying this spec to a
concrete project lives separately (see `CEM_Requirements_Worked_Example.md`).

```
Vision
    │
    ▼
Concept Architecture
    │
    ▼
Requirements   ← this document
    │
    ▼
Decision Records
    │
    ▼
System Architecture
    │
    ▼
Generated Project
```

## 1. Purpose

Concept Architecture answers: *what functional resources does this system need?* — a technology-independent
decomposition of the system into named subsystems and leaves, with no hardware or software specifics attached.

Requirements answers: *what will have to be determined about each resource before it can be decided or
bought?* It is a manifest of what's needed, not a spec sheet. It exists to guarantee nothing gets skipped, and
to make explicit how much is still unknown, without pretending to know it yet.

Requirements never contains hardware specs, part numbers, voltages, protocols, or vendor detail. That
information belongs to System Architecture, and only appears there after a Decision Record has resolved which
candidate was chosen. This separation is what allows Concept Architecture to remain stable while real-world
implementation details change underneath it.

## 2. Scope: one row per leaf

Every leaf in a Concept Architecture tree gets exactly one Requirements row. A row is not "resolved" at this
stage — resolution happens later, in Decision Records and System Architecture. At the Requirements stage,
every row is expected to be honestly incomplete.

## 3. Node ID

Every row is identified by a **Node ID**: a short, structured identifier generated automatically from the
node's position in its Concept Architecture tree (e.g. `PWR.RECHG.CTRL` for a node nested under a Power
Supply subsystem's Recharging Infrastructure branch).

- Node IDs are **positional**, not assigned by hand, and always reflect current tree structure.
- Two nodes may share a human-readable display name (e.g. "Communications" appearing under two different
  subsystems) — the Node ID disambiguates them without forcing an artificial rename.
- Node IDs are the only safe way to reference one row from another (see Depends On, §6).

## 4. Concept Version

Every row also records the **version of the subsystem's Concept Architecture document it was written
against** (e.g. `PWR-v1`).

Versioning rules:

- **Version scope is per-subsystem, never whole-project.** A structural change to one subsystem's tree bumps
  only that subsystem's version. Other subsystems are unaffected and stay on their current versions.
- **Only a structural change bumps the version.** Structural change means a node is added, removed, or
  re-nested — the tree shape changes. Adding new information to an existing node (e.g. an interface detail
  discovered downstream) is not structural and does not require a version bump; it can be edited in place.
- **A `Depends On` value changing is not a structural change**, even though it references another node — the
  tree shape hasn't moved.
- **No separate deletion log or changelog mechanism is needed.** Because this documentation lives in version
  control, the prior version is preserved in history rather than overwritten. The version bump plus the commit
  itself is the record of what changed; CEM does not need its own changelog format on top of that.

The Concept Version field lets anyone filter for every Requirements row that needs re-review after a
subsystem's structure changes, rather than re-reading the entire table.

## 5. Requirement flags

Four flags per row, each set to **Needed**, **N/A**, or (later) resolved with a decision reference:

| Flag | What it will eventually pin down |
|---|---|
| **Performance** | The measurable behavior this leaf must deliver |
| **Interface** | What it must physically/electrically/logically connect to |
| **Constraint** | Ceilings — cost, power, size, weight — that bound the eventual choice |
| **Make-vs-Buy** | Whether this becomes a purchased component, an integrated library/module, or custom-built |

A flag may legitimately be **N/A** (e.g. Make-vs-Buy doesn't apply to a node that will obviously always be
custom-fabricated). A blank flag is not a legitimate state — every flag must be explicitly set.

## 6. Depends On

A field listing the Node ID(s) of any other row that must be resolved before this row can be. Defaults to
**N/A** automatically; only populated when a real dependency exists.

- This is a **lateral** relationship between rows, distinct from the **vertical** containment relationship
  already expressed by Concept Architecture's tree structure. The two are never conflated or given the same
  name — containment answers "what's inside what," Depends On answers "what must be decided first."
- Depends On stays a simple flat field. The Requirements document is treated as a database: at scale,
  dependency chains are handled by filtering/querying the field, not by a dedicated visual representation. A
  diagram may still be produced to explain any one relationship to a person, but the table is the source of
  truth.

## 7. Status

Every row carries a Status field. At the Requirements stage this starts as **Open**. Once a Decision Record
exists for this row, Status changes to that record's Decision ID (e.g. `DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001`) rather than a
generic label — the row always points to the specific record responsible for resolving it, not just a state
name. If that Decision Record is later superseded (see the Decision Records spec, §7), Status is updated to
the superseding Decision ID.

## 8. Notes

A free-text field for soft, non-binding observations — assumptions, open ambiguities, suggested sequencing.
Nothing in Notes is authoritative; anything that needs to be relied upon belongs in one of the structured
fields above instead.

## 9. Row schema (summary)

| Field | Required | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Node ID | Yes | Auto-generated, positional |
| Node (display name) | Yes | Human-readable; not guaranteed unique |
| Concept Version | Yes | Which version of the subsystem's Concept doc this row reflects |
| Performance | Yes | Needed / N/A |
| Interface | Yes | Needed / N/A |
| Constraint | Yes | Needed / N/A |
| Make-vs-Buy | Yes | Needed / N/A |
| Depends On | Yes | Node ID(s) or N/A (default) |
| Status | Yes | Open, or the Decision ID once one exists |
| Notes | Optional | Non-binding |

## 10. Handoff to Decision Records

Decision Records is where a row's flags get answered against real-world candidates, a Make-vs-Buy call gets
made, and the reasoning is kept. Depends On tells Decision Records which rows are eligible to be resolved
first. Requirements itself is never edited to reflect a decision outcome — only Status changes, from Open to
the Decision ID that now owns this row.
